# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: catalyst-mac
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Cocoa consists of the Foundation Kit, Application Kit, and Core Data frameworks, as included by the `Cocoa.h` header file, and the libraries and frameworks included by those, such as the C standard library and the Objective-C runtime.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Cocoa applications are typically developed using the development tools provided by Apple, specifically Xcode (formerly Project Builder) and Interface Builder (now part of Xcode), using the programming languages Objective-C or Swift.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] However, the Cocoa programming environment can be accessed using other tools.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] It is also possible to write Objective-C Cocoa programs in a simple text editor and build it manually with GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) or Clang from the command line or from a makefile.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] For end users, Cocoa applications are those written using the Cocoa programming environment.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Such applications usually have a familiar look and feel, since the Cocoa programming environment provides a lot of common UI elements (such as buttons, scroll bars, etc.), and automates many aspects of an application to comply with Apple's human interface guidelines.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] For iOS, iPadOS, tvOS, and watchOS, APIs similar to Application Kit, named UIKit and WatchKit, are available; they include gesture recognition, animation, and a different set of graphical control elements that are designed to accommodate the specific platforms they target.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Foundation Kit and Core Data are also available in those operating systems.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] It is used in applications for Apple devices such as the iPhone, the iPod Touch, the iPad, the Apple TV, and the Apple Watch.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Cocoa continues the lineage of several software frameworks (mainly the *App Kit* and *Foundation Kit*) from the NeXTSTEP and OpenStep programming environments developed by NeXT in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Apple acquired NeXT in December 1996, and subsequently went to work on the Rhapsody operating system that was to be the direct successor of OPENSTEP.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] It was to have had an emulation base for classic Mac OS applications, named *Blue Box*.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] The OpenStep base of libraries and binary support was termed *Yellow Box*.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Rhapsody evolved into Mac OS X, and the Yellow Box became Cocoa.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Thus, Cocoa classes begin with the letters *NS*, such as NSString or NSArray.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] These stand for the original proprietary term for the OpenStep framework, NeXTSTEP.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Much of the work that went into developing OpenStep was applied to developing Mac OS X, Cocoa being the most visible part.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] For example, NeXTSTEP and OpenStep used Display PostScript for on-screen display of text and graphics, while Cocoa depends on Apple's Quartz (which uses the Portable Document Format (PDF) imaging model, but not its underlying technology).
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Cocoa also has a level of World Wide Web support, including the NSURL and WebKit HTML classes, and others, while OpenStep had only rudimentary support for managed network connections via NSFileHandle classes and Berkeley sockets.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] The API toolbox was originally called “Yellow Box” and was renamed to Cocoa - a name that had been already trademarked by Apple.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Apple's *Cocoa* trademark had originated as the name of a multimedia project design application for children.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] The name was intended to evoke "Java for kids", as it ran embedded in web pages.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] The original "Cocoa" program was discontinued following the return of Steve Jobs to Apple.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] At the time, Java was a big focus area for the company, so “Cocoa” was used as the new name for “Yellow Box” because, in addition to the native Objective-C usage, it could also be accessed from Java via a bridging layer.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Even though Apple discontinued support for the Cocoa Java bridge, the name continued and was even used for the Cocoa Touch API.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] One feature of the Cocoa environment is its facility for managing dynamically allocated memory.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Foundation Kit's NSObject class, from which most classes, both vendor and user, are derived, implements a reference counting scheme for memory management.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Objects that derive from the NSObject root class respond to a `retain` and a `release` message, and keep a retain count.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] A method titled `retainCount` exists, but contrary to its name, will usually not return the exact retain count of an object.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] It is mainly used for system-level purposes.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Invoking it manually is not recommended by Apple.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] A newly allocated object created with `alloc` or `copy` has a retain count of one.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Sending that object a `retain` message increments the retain count, while sending it a `release` message decrements the retain count.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] When an object's retain count reaches zero, it is deallocated by a procedure similar to a C++ *destructor*.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] `dealloc` is not guaranteed to be invoked.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Starting with Objective-C 2.0, the Objective-C runtime implemented an optional garbage collector, which is now obsolete and deprecated in favor of Automatic Reference Counting (ARC).
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] In this model, the runtime turned Cocoa reference counting operations such as "retain" and "release" into no-ops.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] The garbage collector does not exist on the iOS implementation of Objective-C 2.0.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Garbage collection in Objective-C ran on a low-priority background thread, and can halt on Cocoa's user events, with the intention of keeping the user experience responsive.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] The legacy garbage collector is still available on Mac OS X version 10.13, but no Apple-provided applications use it.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] In 2011, the LLVM compiler introduced Automatic Reference Counting (ARC), which replaces the conventional garbage collector by performing static analysis of Objective-C source code and inserting retain and release messages as necessary.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Cocoa consists of three Objective-C object libraries called *frameworks*.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Frameworks are functionally similar to shared libraries, a compiled object that can be dynamically loaded into a program's address space at runtime, but frameworks add associated resources, header files, and documentation.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] The Cocoa frameworks are implemented as a type of bundle, containing the aforementioned items in standard locations.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] A key part of the Cocoa architecture is its comprehensive views model.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] This is organized along conventional lines for an application framework, but is based on the Portable Document Format (PDF) drawing model provided by Quartz.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] This allows creating custom drawing content using PostScript-like drawing commands, which also allows automatic printer support and so forth.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Since the Cocoa framework manages all the clipping, scrolling, scaling and other chores of drawing graphics, the programmer is freed from implementing basic infrastructure and can concentrate on the unique aspects of an application's content.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] The Smalltalk teams at Xerox PARC eventually settled on a design philosophy that led to easy development and high code reuse.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Cocoa's design is a fairly, but not absolutely strict application of MVC principles.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Under OpenStep, most of the classes provided were either high-level View classes (in AppKit) or one of a number of relatively low-level model classes like NSString.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Compared to similar MVC systems, OpenStep lacked a strong model layer.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] No stock class represented a "document," for instance.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] During the transition to Cocoa, the model layer was expanded greatly, introducing a number of pre-rolled classes to provide functionality common to desktop applications.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] In Mac OS X 10.3, Apple introduced the NSController family of classes, which provide predefined behavior for the controller layer.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] These classes are considered part of the Cocoa Bindings system, which also makes extensive use of protocols such as Key-Value Observing and Key-Value Binding.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] The term 'binding' refers to a relationship between two objects, often between a view and a controller.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Bindings allow the developer to focus more on declarative relationships rather than orchestrating fine-grained behavior.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] With the arrival of Mac OS X 10.4, Apple extended this foundation further by introducing the Core Data framework, which standardizes change tracking and persistence in the model layer.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] In effect, the framework greatly simplifies the process of making changes to application data, undoing changes when necessary, saving data to disk, and reading it back in.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] In providing framework support for all three MVC domains, Apple's goal is to reduce the amount of boilerplate or "glue" code that developers have to write, freeing up resources to spend time on application-specific features.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] In most object-oriented languages, calls to methods are represented physically by a pointer to the code in memory.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] This restricts the design of an application since specific *command handling* classes are needed, usually organized according to the chain-of-responsibility pattern.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] While Cocoa retains this approach for the most part, Objective-C's late binding opens up more flexibility.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Under Objective-C, methods are represented by a *selector*, a string describing the method to call.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] When a message is sent, the selector is sent into the Objective-C runtime, matched against a list of available methods, and the method's *implementation* is called.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Since the selector is text data, this lets it be saved to a file, transmitted over a network or between processes, or manipulated in other ways.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] The implementation of the method is looked up at runtime, not compile time.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] There is a small performance penalty for this, but late binding allows the same selector to reference different implementations.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] By a similar token, Cocoa provides a pervasive data manipulation method called *key-value coding* (KVC).
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] This allows a piece of data or property of an object to be looked up or changed at runtime by name.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] The property name acts as a key to the value.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] In traditional languages, this late binding is impossible.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] An object's type need not be known, yet any property of that object can be discovered using KVC.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Also, by extending this system using something Cocoa terms *key-value observing* (KVO), automatic support for undo-redo is provided.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Late static binding is a variant of binding somewhere between static and dynamic binding.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] The binding of names before the program is run is called static (*early*); bindings performed as the program runs are dynamic (*late* or *virtual*).
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] One of the most useful features of Cocoa is the powerful *base objects* the system supplies.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] As an example, consider the Foundation classes `NSString` and `NSAttributedString`, which provide Unicode strings, and the `NSText` system in AppKit, which allows the programmer to place string objects in the GUI.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] `NSText` and its related classes are used to display and edit strings.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Paragraph layout can be controlled automatically or by the user, using a built-in "ruler" object that can be attached to any text view.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Spell checking is automatic, using a system-wide set of language dictionaries.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Unlimited undo/redo support is built in.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Using only the built-in features, one can write a text editor application in as few as 10 lines of code.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] With new controller objects, this may fall towards zero.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] When extensions are needed, Cocoa's use of Objective-C makes this a straightforward task.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Objective-C includes the concept of "categories," which allows modifying existing class "in-place".
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Functionality can be accomplished in a category without any changes to the original classes in the framework, or even access to its source.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] In other common languages, this same task requires deriving a new subclass supporting the added features, and then replacing all instances of the original class with instances of the new subclass.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] The Cocoa frameworks are written in Objective-C.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Cocoa's need for runtime binding means many of Cocoa's key features are not available with Java.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] In 2005, Apple announced that the Java bridge was to be deprecated, meaning that features added to Cocoa in macOS versions later than 10.4 would not be added to the Cocoa-Java programming interface.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] At Apple Worldwide Developers Conference (WWDC) 2014, Apple introduced a new programming language named Swift, which is intended to replace Objective-C.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Originally, AppleScript Studio could be used to develop simpler Cocoa applications.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] However, as of Snow Leopard, it has been deprecated.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] It was replaced with AppleScriptObjC, which allows programming in AppleScript, while using Cocoa frameworks.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] The Cocoa programming environment can be accessed using other tools with the aid of bridge mechanisms such as PasCocoa, PyObjC, CamelBones, RubyCocoa, and a D/Objective-C Bridge.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] Third-party bindings available for other languages include AppleScript, Clozure CL, Monobjc and NObjective (C#), Cocoa# (CLI), Cocodao and D/Objective-C Bridge, LispWorks, Object Pascal, CamelBones (Perl), PyObjC (Python), FPC PasCocoa (Lazarus and Free Pascal), RubyCocoa (Ruby).
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] A Ruby language implementation named MacRuby, which removes the need for a bridge mechanism, was formerly developed by Apple, while Nu is a Lisp-like language that uses the Objective-C object model directly, and thus can use the Cocoa frameworks without needing a binding.
[src:catalyst-mac/cocoa-api] There are also open source implementations of major parts of the Cocoa framework, such as GNUstep and Cocotron, which allow cross-platform Cocoa application development to target other operating systems, such as Microsoft Windows and Linux.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] The first iPad was introduced on April 3, 2010, and ran iPhone OS 3.2, which added support for the larger device to the operating system, previously only used on the iPhone and its smaller counterpart, the iPod touch.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] This shared operating system was rebranded as iOS with the release of iOS 4 in June 2010.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] The operating system initially had rough feature parity running on the iPhone, iPod Touch, and iPad, with variations in user interface depending on screen size, and minor differences in the selection of apps included.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] Standard iPad apps were increasingly designed to support the optional use of a physical keyboard.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] To emphasize the different feature set available on the iPad, and to signal their intention to develop the platforms in divergent directions, at the Worldwide Developers Conference (WWDC) 2019, Apple announced that the variant of iOS that runs on the iPad would be rebranded as "iPadOS".
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] The new naming strategy began with iPadOS 13.1, in 2019.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] On June 22, 2020, at WWDC 2020, Apple announced iPadOS 14, with compact designs for search, Siri, and calls, improved app designs, handwriting recognition, better AR features, enhanced privacy protections, and app widgets. iPadOS 14 was released to the public on September 16, 2020.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] On June 7, 2021, at WWDC 2021, iPadOS 15 was announced with widgets on the Home Screen and App Library, the same features that came to iPhone with iOS 14 in 2020.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] The update also brought stricter privacy measurements with Safari such as IP Address blocking so other websites cannot see it. iPadOS 15 was released to the public on September 20, 2021.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] On June 6, 2022, at WWDC 2022, iPadOS 16 was announced with a Weather app and Stage Manager, along with most of the features included in iOS 16, excluding a customizable lock screen.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] On June 5, 2023, at WWDC 2023, Apple announced iPadOS 17 with support for widgets for the lock screen, a feature originally launched with iOS 16, along with the majority of features announced included in iOS 17.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] In addition, iPadOS 17 now includes the Apple Health app.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] On June 10, 2024, at WWDC 2024, Apple announced iPadOS 18.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] On June 9, 2025, at WWDC 2025, Apple announced iPadOS 26.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] On June 8, 2026, at WWDC 2026, Apple announced iPadOS 27.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] Many features of iPadOS are also available on iOS; however, iPadOS contains some features and apps that are not available in iOS and lacks some features and apps that are available in iOS.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] Introduced in iPadOS 14, Scribble converts text handwritten by an Apple Pencil into typed text in most text fields.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] Beginning with iPadOS 15, widgets can be placed on the home screen.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] Beginning with iPadOS 15, Translate is available.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] The feature was announced on June 7, 2021, at WWDC 2021.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] Beginning with iPadOS 16, the Weather app was added to iPad.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] The application had previously only been available on the iPhone and iPod Touch.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] The feature was announced on June 6, 2022, at WWDC 2022.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] iPadOS 16 adds a new feature called Stage Manager that automatically sorts windows by app.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] iPadOS 17 allows users to personalize their Lock Screens with widgets and fonts.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] Interactive widgets can be placed on both the Lock Screen and Home Screen for quick access to customizable information, such as weather and reminders.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] The introduction of the Health app on iPad provides a central location to view and manage health data.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] New communication features for Messages and FaceTime were introduced, such as audio messages (like a voicemail) if a call is not answered on FaceTime, and using an Apple TV for FaceTime calls with an iPad acting as a camera.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] Messages introduces the combining of search filters and content types when users search through messages, as well as transcriptions for audio messages.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] New accessibility features such as Screen Distance and improved Voice Control expand usability options for a wider range of users.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] Several core apps receive updates, including Photos, Safari, Notes, and Reminders, bringing new functionality and improvements to enhance the overall iPad experience.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] iPadOS 18 introduces Apple Intelligence with artificial intelligence (AI) capabilities.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] Users can place apps and widgets anywhere on the Home Screen, and set a dark-themed or tinted look for app icons.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] The Calculator app for iPad was introduced.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] The Control Center was redesigned to be customizable with resizable buttons, shortcuts, and functions.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] Users can set apps to be locked or hidden; accessing such apps requires passcode or biometric authentication.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] iPadOS 26 has a new Liquid Glass design, new apps including Phone, Games, Journal and Preview, and a windowing system similar to macOS for multitasking.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] Folder icons are also more customizable.
[src:catalyst-mac/ipados] iPadOS 27 introduces new features and enhancements to Apple Intelligence and child-safety features.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] The operating system is named after Santa Catalina Island, which is located off the coast of southern California.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] macOS Catalina is the final version of macOS that supports the Unibody MacBook Pro, as its successor, macOS Big Sur, drops support for its mid-2012 and final model.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] All standard configuration Macs that supported macOS Mojave support macOS Catalina.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] 2010 to 2012 Mac Pros, which could run Mojave only with a GPU upgrade, are not supported.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] Catalina requires 4 GB of memory, an increase over the 2 GB required by Lion through Mojave.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] It is unofficially possible to install macOS Catalina on many older Macintosh computers that are not officially supported by Apple.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] This requires using a patch to modify the install image.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] Catalyst is a software-development tool that allows developers to write apps that can run on macOS, iOS and iPadOS.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] Apple demonstrated several ported apps, including Jira and Twitter (after the latter discontinued its macOS app in February 2018).
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] System extensions avoid the problems of Kexts.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] There are 3 kinds of System extensions: Network Extensions, Endpoint Security Extensions, and Driver Extensions.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] System extensions run in userspace, outside of the kernel.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] Catalina will be the last version of macOS to support legacy system extensions.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] A replacement for IOKit device drivers, driver extensions are built using DriverKit.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] DriverKit is a new SDK with all-new frameworks based on IOKit, but updated and modernized.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] It is designed for building device drivers in userspace, outside of the kernel.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] Mac apps, installer packages, and kernel extensions that are signed with a Developer ID must be notarized by Apple to run on macOS Catalina.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] Activation Lock prevents the unauthorized use and drive erasure of devices with an Apple T2 security chip (2018, 2019, and 2020 MacBook Pro; 2020 5K iMac; 2018 MacBook Air, iMac Pro; 2018 Mac Mini; 2019 Mac Pro).
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] The system runs on its own read-only volume, separate from all other data on the Mac.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] Users can give detailed voice commands to applications.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] On-device machine processing is used to offer better navigation.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] Sidecar allows a Mac to use an iPad (running iPadOS) as a wireless external display.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] With Apple Pencil, the device can also be used as a graphics tablet for software running on the computer.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] Sidecar requires a Mac with Intel Skylake CPUs and newer (such as the fourth-generation MacBook Pro), and an iPad that supports Apple Pencil.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] The Game Controller framework adds support for two major console game controllers: the PlayStation 4's DualShock 4 and the Xbox One controller.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] A number of under-the-hood changes were made to Time Machine, macOS's backup software.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] One change was the manner in which backup data is stored on network-attached devices was changed, and this change is not backwards-compatible with earlier versions of macOS.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] Apple declined to document these changes, but some of them have been noted.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] macOS Catalina 10.15.2 adds compatibility with the Pro Display XDR and enables 6016×3384 output on the 2019 iMac and 2018 15-inch MacBook Pro.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] iTunes is replaced by separate Music, Podcasts, TV and Books apps, in line with iOS. iOS device management is now conducted via Finder.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] The TV app on Mac supports Dolby Atmos, Dolby Vision, and HDR10 on MacBooks released in 2018 or later, while 4K HDR playback is supported on Macs released in 2018 or later when connected to a compatible display.
[src:catalyst-mac/mac-catalyst] Find My Mac and the Find My Friends widget were merged into Find My.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Mac OS X succeeded the classic Mac OS, the primary Macintosh operating system from 1984 to 2001.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Its underlying architecture came from NeXT's NeXTSTEP, as a result of Apple's acquisition of NeXT, which also brought Steve Jobs back to Apple.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The first desktop version, Mac OS X 10.0, was released on March 24, 2001.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Apart from OS X Lion, all versions from Mac OS X Leopard onwards are UNIX 03 certified.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Each of Apple's other contemporary operating systems, including iOS, iPadOS, watchOS, tvOS, audioOS and visionOS, are derivatives of macOS.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] During its history, macOS has supported three major processor architectures: the initial version supported PowerPC-based Macs only, with support for Intel-based Macs beginning with OS X Tiger 10.4.4 and support for ARM-based Apple silicon Macs beginning with macOS Big Sur.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Support for PowerPC-based Macs was dropped with OS X Snow Leopard, and it was announced at the 2025 Worldwide Developers Conference that macOS Tahoe will be the last to support Intel-based Macs.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Unlike versions of the classic Mac OS, Mac OS X retained the same major version number (10) for almost two decades, with major releases only incrementing the *minor* version number (e.g.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Since 2020, Apple increments the major version component in each major release, with macOS Big Sur getting version number 11.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] In 2025, the numbering scheme was changed once again, now using the number of the year that follows the release year (e.g. macOS Tahoe, released in September 2025, has a version number 26).
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] A prominent part of macOS's original brand identity was the use of the Roman numeral X, pronounced "ten", as well as code naming each release after species of big cats, and later, places within California.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Apple shortened the name to "OS X" in 2011 and then changed it to "macOS" in 2016 to align with the branding of Apple's other operating systems.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] In 2020, macOS Big Sur was presented as version 11—a marked departure after 16 releases of macOS 10—but the naming convention continued to reference places within California.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] In 2025, Apple unified the version number across all of its products to align with the year after their WWDC announcement, so the release announced at the 2025 WWDC, macOS Tahoe, is macOS 26.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The heritage of what would become macOS originated at NeXT, a company founded by Steve Jobs following his departure from Apple in 1985.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] There, the Unix-like NeXTSTEP operating system was developed, before being launched in 1989.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The kernel of NeXTSTEP is based upon the Mach kernel, which was originally developed at Carnegie Mellon University, with additional kernel layers and low-level user space code derived from parts of FreeBSD and other BSD operating systems.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Its graphical user interface was built on top of an object-oriented GUI toolkit using the Objective-C programming language.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Throughout the 1990s, Apple had tried to create a "next-generation" OS to succeed its classic Mac OS through the Taligent, Copland and Gershwin projects; however, all were eventually abandoned.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] This led Apple to acquire NeXT in 1997, allowing NeXTSTEP, later called OPENSTEP, to serve as the basis for Apple's next-generation operating system.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The acquisition also led to Steve Jobs returning to Apple as interim and later permanent CEO, shepherding the transformation of the programmer-friendly OPENSTEP into a system that would be adopted by Apple's primary market of home users and creative professionals.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The project was codenamed "Rhapsody" before being officially named Mac OS X.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The "X" in Mac OS X's name represents the Roman numeral for the number ten, and Apple has stated that it should be pronounced "ten" in this context; it is also commonly pronounced like the letter "X".
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The iPhone X, iPhone XR and iPhone XS all later followed this convention.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The first version of Mac OS X, Mac OS X Server 1.0, was a transitional product, featuring an interface resembling the classic Mac OS, though it was not compatible with software designed for the older system; consumer releases of Mac OS X included more backward compatibility.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Mac OS applications could be rewritten to run natively via the Carbon API, with many alternatively able to be run directly through the Classic Environment albeit with a reduction in performance.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The consumer version of Mac OS X was launched in March 2001 with Mac OS X 10.0.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Reviews were variable, with many praising its sophisticated, glossy Aqua interface, but criticizing it for sluggish performance.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] With Apple's popularity at a low, the developer of FrameMaker, Adobe Inc., declined to develop new versions of it for Mac OS X.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] *Ars Technica* columnist John Siracusa, who reviewed every major OS X release up to 10.10, described the early releases in retrospect as "dog-slow, feature poor" and Aqua as "unbearably slow and a huge resource hog".
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Apple rapidly developed several new releases of Mac OS X.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Apple released Mac OS X 10.1 in October 2001, delivering quality of life enhancements.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Beginning in January 2002, Apple preinstalled Mac OS X as the default operating system on all Macs.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Later that year Apple released Mac OS X Jaguar (version 10.2), the first version to publicly use its code name in marketing and advertisements.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] As the operating system evolved, it moved away from the classic Mac OS, with applications being added and removed.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Considering music to be a key market, Apple developed the iPod music player and music software for the Mac, including iTunes and GarageBand.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Targeting the consumer and media markets, Apple emphasized its new "digital lifestyle" applications such as the iLife suite, integrated home entertainment through the Front Row media center and the Safari web browser.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] With the increasing popularity of the internet, Apple offered additional online services, including the .Mac, MobileMe, and later, iCloud products.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] It later began selling third-party applications through the Mac App Store.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Newer versions of Mac OS X also included modifications to the general interface, moving away from the striped gloss and transparency of the initial versions.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Some applications began to use a brushed metal appearance, or non-pinstriped title bar appearance in Mac OS X Tiger.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] In Mac OS X Leopard (10.5), Apple announced a unification of the interface, with a standardized gray-gradient window style.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] In 2006, the first Intel Macs were released with a specialized version of Mac OS X Tiger.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] A key development for the system was the announcement and release of the iPhone from 2007 onwards.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] While Apple's previous iPod media players used a minimal operating system, the iPhone used an operating system based on Mac OS X, which would later be called iPhone OS and then iOS.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The simultaneous release of two operating systems based on the same frameworks placed tension on Apple, which cited the iPhone as forcing it to delay Mac OS X Leopard.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] However, after Apple opened the iPhone to third-party developers, its commercial success drew attention to Mac OS X, with many iPhone software developers showing interest in Mac development.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] In 2007, Mac OS X Leopard released with universal binary components, allowing installation on both Intel Macs and select PowerPC Macs.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] It is also the final release with PowerPC Mac support.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] In 2009, Mac OS X Snow Leopard (10.6) was the first version of Mac OS X to be built exclusively for Intel Macs and the final release with 32-bit Intel Mac support.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The name was intended to signal its status as an iteration of Leopard, focusing on technical and performance improvements rather than user-facing features; indeed it was explicitly branded to developers as being a 'no new features' release.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Since its release, several OS X or macOS releases (namely OS X Mountain Lion, OS X El Capitan, macOS High Sierra, and macOS Monterey) follow this pattern, with a name derived from its predecessor, similar to the 'tick–tock model' used by Intel.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Starting in 2011 with Mac OS X Lion (10.7) and OS X Mountain Lion (10.8), Apple moved some applications to a highly skeuomorphic style of design inspired by contemporary versions of iOS while simplifying some elements by making controls such as scroll bars fade out when not in use.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] In addition, with Lion, Apple ceased to release separate server versions of Mac OS X, selling server tools as a separate downloadable application through the Mac App Store.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] In 2012, with the release of OS X Mountain Lion, the name of the system was officially shortened from Mac OS X to OS X, after the previous version shortened the system name in a similar fashion a year prior.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] That year, Apple removed the head of OS X development, Scott Forstall, and design was changed towards a more minimal direction.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Apple's new user interface design, using deep color saturation, text-only buttons and a minimal, 'flat' interface, was debuted with iOS 7 in 2013.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] With OS X engineers reportedly working on iOS 7, the version released in 2013, OS X Mavericks (10.9), was something of a transitional release, with some of the skeuomorphic design removed, while most of the general interface of Mavericks remained unchanged.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The next version, OS X Yosemite (10.10), adopted a design similar to iOS 7 but with greater complexity suitable for an interface controlled with a mouse.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] From 2012 onwards, the system has shifted to an annual release schedule similar to that of Mac OS X releases prior to 10.4 Tiger.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] It also steadily cut the cost of updates from Snow Leopard onwards, before removing upgrade fees altogether in OS X Mavericks.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Some journalists and third-party software developers have suggested that this decision, while allowing more rapid feature release, meant less opportunity to focus on stability, with no version of OS X recommendable for users requiring stability and performance above new features.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Apple's 2015 update, OS X El Capitan (10.11), was announced to focus specifically on stability and performance improvements.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Its successor, macOS Mojave (10.14), was released in 2018, adding a dark mode option and a dynamic wallpaper setting.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] It was succeeded by macOS Catalina (10.15) in 2019, which replaces iTunes with separate apps for different types of media, and introduces the Catalyst system for porting iOS apps.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] In 2020, Apple announced macOS Big Sur (version 11) at that year's WWDC.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] This was the first increment in the primary version number of macOS since the release of Mac OS X Public Beta in 2000; updates to macOS Big Sur were given 11.x numbers, matching the version numbering scheme used by Apple's other operating systems.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Big Sur brought major changes to the user interface and was the first version to run on Apple Silicon, based on the ARM architecture.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The numbering system started with Big Sur continued in 2021 with macOS Monterey (12), 2022 with macOS Ventura (13), 2023 with macOS Sonoma (14), and 2024 with macOS Sequoia (15).
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] During its Platforms State of the Union event on June 9, 2025, Apple announced that Tahoe would be the final version of macOS to operate on Intel-based Macs.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] In 2026, Apple announced macOS Golden Gate (version 27) at WWDC 2026.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] It will be the first version of macOS to run exclusively on Macs with Apple silicon and the last version with full Rosetta 2 functionality.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The Power Mac G5 had special Jaguar builds.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Tiger did not support 64-bit GUI applications, only 64-bit CLI applications.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] 32-bit (but not 64-bit) PowerPC applications were supported on Intel processors with Rosetta.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] 64-bit Intel applications are supported on Apple silicon Macs with Rosetta 2.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] However, Intel-based Macs are unable to run ARM-based applications, such as iOS and iPadOS apps.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] At macOS's core is a POSIX-compliant operating system built on top of the XNU kernel, (which incorporated large parts of FreeBSD kernel) and FreeBSD userland for the standard Unix facilities available from the command line interface.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Apple has released this family of software as a free and open source operating system named Darwin.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] On top of Darwin, Apple layered a number of components, including the Aqua interface and the Finder, to complete the GUI-based operating system which is macOS.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] With its original introduction as Mac OS X, the system brought a number of new capabilities to provide a more stable and reliable platform than its predecessor, the classic Mac OS.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] For example, pre-emptive multitasking and memory protection improved the system's ability to run multiple applications simultaneously without them interrupting or corrupting each other.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Many aspects of macOS's architecture are derived from OPENSTEP, which was designed to be portable, to ease the transition from one platform to another.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] For example, NeXTSTEP was ported from the original 68k-based NeXT workstations to x86 and other architectures before NeXT was purchased by Apple, and OPENSTEP was later ported to the PowerPC architecture as part of the Rhapsody project.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Prior to macOS High Sierra, and on drives other than solid state drives (SSDs), the default file system is HFS+, which it inherited from the classic Mac OS.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Operating system designer Linus Torvalds had criticized HFS+, saying it is "probably the worst file system ever", whose design is "actively corrupting user data".
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] He criticized the case insensitivity of file names, a design made worse when Apple extended the file system to support Unicode.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The Darwin subsystem in macOS manages the file system, which includes the Unix permissions layer.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Later, another Macworld editor, Dan Frakes, called the procedure of repairing permissions vastly overused.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] He argues that macOS typically handles permissions properly without user interference, and resetting permissions should only be tried when problems emerge.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The architecture of macOS incorporates a layered design: the layered frameworks aid rapid development of applications by providing existing code for common tasks.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Apple provides its own software development tools, most prominently an integrated development environment called Xcode.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Xcode provides interfaces to compilers that support several programming languages including C, C++, Objective-C, and Swift.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] For the Mac transition to Intel processors, it was modified so that developers could build their applications as a universal binary, which provides compatibility with both the Intel-based and PowerPC-based Macintosh lines.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] First and third-party applications can be controlled programmatically using the AppleScript framework, retained from the classic Mac OS, or using the newer Automator application that offers pre-written tasks that do not require programming knowledge.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Apple offered two main APIs to develop software natively for macOS: Cocoa and Carbon.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Cocoa was a descendant of APIs inherited from OPENSTEP with no ancestry from the classic Mac OS, while Carbon was an adaptation of classic Mac OS APIs, allowing Mac software to be minimally rewritten to run natively on Mac OS X.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The Cocoa API was created as the result of a 1993 collaboration between NeXT Computer and Sun Microsystems.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] This heritage is highly visible for Cocoa developers, since the "NS" prefix is ubiquitous in the framework, standing variously for **N**eXT**S**TEP or **N**eXT/**S**un.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The official OPENSTEP API, published in September 1994, was the first to split the API between Foundation and ApplicationKit and the first to use the "NS" prefix.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Traditionally, Cocoa programs have been mostly written in Objective-C, with Java as an alternative.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Since 2014, Apple has promoted its new programming language Swift as the preferred language for software development on Apple platforms.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Apple's original plan with macOS was to require all developers to rewrite their software into the Cocoa APIs.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] This caused much outcry among existing Mac developers, who threatened to abandon the platform rather than invest in a costly rewrite, and the idea was shelved.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] To permit a smooth transition from Mac OS 9 to Mac OS X, the Carbon Application Programming Interface (API) was created.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Applications written with Carbon were initially able to run natively on both classic Mac OS and Mac OS X, although this ability was later dropped as Mac OS X developed.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Carbon was not included in the first product sold as Mac OS X: the little-used original release of Mac OS X Server 1.0, which also did not include the Aqua interface.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Apple limited further development of Carbon from the release of Leopard onwards and announced that Carbon applications would not run at 64-bit.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] A number of macOS applications continued to use Carbon for some time afterwards, especially ones with heritage dating back to the classic Mac OS and for which updates would be difficult, uneconomic or not necessary.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] This included Microsoft Office up to Office 2016, and Photoshop up to CS5.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Early versions of macOS could also run some classic Mac OS applications through the Classic Environment with performance limitations; this feature was removed from 10.5 onwards and all Macs using Intel processors.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Because macOS is POSIX compliant, many software packages written for the other Unix-like systems including Linux can be recompiled to run on it, including many scientific and technical programs.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Third-party projects such as Homebrew, Fink, MacPorts and pkgsrc provide pre-compiled or pre-formatted packages.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Apple and others have provided versions of the X Window System graphical interface which can allow these applications to run with an approximation of the macOS look-and-feel.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The current Apple-endorsed method is the open-source XQuartz project; earlier versions could use the X11 application provided by Apple, or before that the XDarwin project.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Apps installed through the Mac App Store run within a sandbox, restricting their ability to exchange information with other applications or modify the core operating system and its features.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] This has been cited as an advantage, by allowing users to install apps with confidence that they should not be able to damage their system, but also as a disadvantage due to blocking the Mac App Store's use for professional applications that require elevated privileges.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Applications without any code signature cannot be run by default except from a computer's administrator account.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Some are included with macOS and some sold separately.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] This includes iWork, Final Cut Pro, Logic Pro, iLife, and the database application FileMaker.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Numerous other developers also offer software for macOS.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] In 2018, Apple introduced an application layer, codenamed Marzipan, to port iOS apps to macOS. macOS Mojave included ports of four first-party iOS apps including Home and News, and it was announced that the API would be available for third-party developers to use from 2019.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] With macOS Catalina in 2019, the application layer was made available to third-party developers as Mac Catalyst.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Tools such as XPostFacto and patches applied to the installation media have been developed by third parties to enable installation of newer versions of macOS on systems not officially supported by Apple.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Except for features requiring specific hardware such as graphics acceleration or DVD writing, the operating system offers the same functionality on all supported hardware.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] As most Mac hardware components, or components similar to those, since the Intel transition are available for purchase, some technology-capable groups have developed software to install macOS on non-Apple computers.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] These are referred to as Hackintoshes, a portmanteau of the words "hack" and "Macintosh".
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] This violates Apple's EULA (and is therefore unsupported by Apple technical support, warranties etc.), but communities that cater to personal users, who do not install for resale and profit, have generally been ignored by Apple.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] These self-made computers allow more flexibility and customization of hardware, but at a cost of leaving the user more responsible for their own machine, such as on matter of data integrity or security.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Psystar, a business that attempted to profit from selling macOS on non-Apple certified hardware, was sued by Apple in 2008.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] In April 2002, eWeek announced a rumor that Apple had a version of Mac OS X code-named Marklar, which ran on Intel x86 processors.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The idea behind Marklar was to keep Mac OS X running on an alternative platform should Apple become dissatisfied with the progress of the PowerPC platform.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] These rumors subsided until late in May 2005, when various media outlets, such as *The Wall Street Journal* and CNET, announced that Apple would unveil Marklar in the coming months.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] On June 6, 2005, Steve Jobs announced in his keynote address at WWDC that Apple would be making the transition from PowerPC to Intel processors over the following two years, and that Mac OS X would support both platforms during the transition.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Jobs also confirmed rumors that Apple had versions of Mac OS X running on Intel processors for most of its developmental life.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Intel-based Macs would run a new recompiled version of OS X along with Rosetta, a binary translation layer which enables software compiled for PowerPC Mac OS X to run on Intel Mac OS X machines.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The system was included with Mac OS X versions up to version 10.6.8.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Apple dropped support for Classic mode on the new Intel Macs.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Third party emulation software such as Mini vMac, Basilisk II and SheepShaver provided support for some early versions of Mac OS.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] A new version of Xcode and the underlying command-line compilers supported building universal binaries that would run on either architecture.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] PowerPC-only software is supported with Apple's official binary translation software, Rosetta, though applications eventually had to be rewritten to run properly on the newer versions released for Intel processors.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Apple initially encouraged developers to produce universal binaries with support for both PowerPC and Intel.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] PowerPC binaries suffer a performance penalty when run on Intel Macs through Rosetta.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Moreover, some PowerPC software, such as kernel extensions and System Preferences plugins, are not supported on Intel Macs at all.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Plugins for Safari need to be compiled for the same platform as Safari, so when Safari is running on Intel, it requires plug-ins that have been compiled as Intel-only or universal binaries, so PowerPC-only plug-ins will not work.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] While Intel Macs can run PowerPC, Intel, and universal binaries, PowerPC Macs support only universal and PowerPC builds.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Support for the PowerPC platform was dropped following the transition.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] In 2009, Apple announced at WWDC that Mac OS X 10.6 Snow Leopard would drop support for PowerPC processors and be Intel-only.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Rosetta continued to be offered as an optional download or installation choice in Snow Leopard before it was discontinued with Mac OS X 10.7 Lion.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] In addition, new versions of Mac OS X first- and third-party software increasingly required Intel processors, including new versions of iLife, iWork, Aperture and Logic Pro.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Rumors of Apple shifting Macs from Intel to in-house ARM processors used by iOS devices began circulating as early as 2011, and ebbed and flowed throughout the 2010s.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Rumors intensified in 2020, when numerous reports announced that the company would announce its shift to its custom processors at WWDC.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Apple officially announced its shift to processors designed in-house on June 22, 2020, at WWDC 2020, with the transition planned to last for approximately two years.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The first release of macOS to support ARM was macOS Big Sur.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Big Sur and later versions support Universal 2 binaries, which are applications consisting of both Intel (x86-64) and Apple silicon (AArch64) binaries; when launched, only the appropriate binary is run.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Additionally, Intel binaries can be run on Apple silicon-based Macs using the Rosetta 2 binary translation software.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The transition was completed at WWDC 2023 with the announcement of the Apple silicon Mac Pro, ending the transition in 3 years, slightly behind schedule.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The change in processor architecture allows Macs with ARM processors to be able to run iOS and iPadOS apps natively.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The macOS user interface places a menu bar along the top edge of the screen, containing the Apple menu and application menus at the start, and status menus at the end.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The Dock is placed along the bottom of the screen by default, and contains icons for pinned and active applications, file and folder shortcuts, minimized windows, and the Trash (or Bin).
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] On most windows, the start of the title bar has three buttons resembling a horizontal traffic light, which respectively close, minimize, and resize the window.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Apple has continued to change aspects of the macOS appearance and design, particularly with tweaks to the appearance of windows and the menu bar.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Since 2012, Apple has sold almost all of its Mac models with high-resolution Retina displays, and macOS and its APIs have extensive support for resolution-independent development on supporting high-resolution displays.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Reviewers have described Apple's support for the technology as superior to that on Windows.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The human interface guidelines published by Apple for macOS are followed by many applications, giving them consistent user interface and keyboard shortcuts.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Services available in every Cocoa application include spelling and grammar checkers, special characters palette, color picker, font chooser and dictionary.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The graphics system OpenGL composites windows onto the screen to allow hardware-accelerated drawing.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] This technology, introduced in version 10.2, is called Quartz Extreme, a component of Quartz.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Quartz's internal imaging model correlates well with the Portable Document Format (PDF) imaging model, making it easy to output PDF to multiple devices.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] As a side result, PDF viewing and creating PDF documents from any application are built-in features.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Reflecting its popularity with design users, macOS also has system support for a variety of professional video and image formats and includes an extensive pre-installed font library, featuring many prominent brand-name designs.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] A major addition between the classic Mac OS and the first major release of Mac OS X was Aqua, a design language with water-like elements.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Every window element, text, graphic, or widget was drawn on-screen using spatial anti-aliasing technology.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The preexisting ColorSync technology was improved and built into the core drawing engine, to provide color matching for printing and multimedia professionals.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Drop shadows were added around windows and isolated text elements to provide a sense of depth.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] New interface elements were integrated, including sheets (dialog boxes attached to specific windows) and drawers, which would slide out and provide options.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The use of soft edges, translucent colors, and pinstripes, similar to the hardware design of the first iMacs, brought more texture and color to the user interface when compared to what Mac OS 9 and Mac OS X Server 1.0's Platinum appearance had offered.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Third-party developers started producing skins for customizable applications and other operating systems which mimicked the Aqua appearance.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] To some extent, Apple has used the successful transition to this design as leverage, at various times threatening legal action against people who make or distribute software with an interface the company says is derived from its copyrighted design.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Following a similar design change in iOS 7, OS X Yosemite shifted to a flat design language, simplifying many of the Aqua elements and icons.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] In 2025, macOS Tahoe adopted the Liquid Glass design language, which was inspired in part by Aqua.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The Finder is a file browser allowing quick access to all areas of the computer, which has been modified throughout subsequent releases of macOS.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Quick Look has been part of the Finder since version 10.5.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] It allows for dynamic previews of files, including videos and multi-page documents without opening any other applications.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Spotlight, a file searching technology which has been integrated into the Finder since version 10.4, allows rapid real-time searches of data files; mail messages; photos; and other information based on item properties (metadata) or content.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Apple added Exposé in version 10.3 (called Mission Control since version 10.7), a feature which includes three functions to help accessibility between windows and desktop.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Its functions are to instantly reveal all open windows as thumbnails for easy navigation to different tasks, display all open windows as thumbnails from the current application, and hide all windows to access the desktop.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] FileVault is optional encryption of the user's files with the 128-bit Advanced Encryption Standard (AES-128).
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Sync Services allows applications to access a centralized extensible database for various elements of user data, including calendar and contact items.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] The operating system then managed conflicting edits and data consistency.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Apple has developed support for emoji characters by including the proprietary Apple Color Emoji font.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Apple has also connected macOS with social networks such as Twitter and Facebook through the addition of share buttons for content such as pictures and text.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Apple has brought several applications and features that originally debuted in iOS, its mobile operating system, to macOS, notably the intelligent personal assistant Siri, which was introduced in version 10.12 of macOS.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] There are 47 system languages available in macOS for the user at the moment of installation; the system language is used throughout the entire operating system environment.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Input methods for typing in dozens of scripts can be chosen independently of the system language.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Updates have added increased support for Chinese characters and interconnections with popular social networks in China.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] macOS can be updated using the Software Update settings pane in System Settings or the `softwareupdate` command line utility.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Until OS X 10.8 Mountain Lion, a separate Software Update application performed this functionality.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] In Mountain Lion and later, this was merged into the Mac App Store application, although the underlying update mechanism remains unchanged and is fundamentally different from the download mechanism used when purchasing an App Store application.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] In macOS 10.14 Mojave, the updating function was moved again to the Software Update settings pane.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] Most Macs receive six or seven years of macOS updates.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p01] After a new major release of macOS, the previous two releases still receive occasional updates, but many security vulnerabilities are only patched in the latest macOS release.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Mac OS X versions were named after big cats, with the exception of Mac OS X Server 1.0 and the original public beta, from Mac OS X 10.0 until OS X 10.9 Mavericks, when Apple switched to using California locations.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Prior to its release, version 10.0 was code named internally at Apple as "Cheetah", and Mac OS X 10.1 was code named internally as "Puma".
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] After the immense buzz surrounding Mac OS X 10.2, codenamed "Jaguar", Apple's product marketing began openly using the code names to promote the operating system.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Mac OS X 10.3 was marketed as "Panther", Mac OS X 10.4 as "Tiger", Mac OS X 10.5 as "Leopard", Mac OS X 10.6 as "Snow Leopard", Mac OS X 10.7 as "Lion", OS X 10.8 as "Mountain Lion", and OS X 10.9 as "Mavericks".
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] "Panther", "Tiger" and "Leopard" are registered as trademarks of Apple, but "Cheetah", "Puma" and "Jaguar" have never been registered.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Apple has also registered "Lynx" and "Cougar" as trademarks, though these were allowed to lapse.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Computer retailer Tiger Direct sued Apple for its use of the name "Tiger".
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] On May 16, 2005, a US federal court in the Southern District of Florida ruled that Apple's use did not infringe on Tiger Direct's trademark.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] On September 13, 2000, Apple released a US$29.95 "preview" version of Mac OS X, internally codenamed Kodiak, to gain feedback from users.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] The "PB", as it was known, marked the first public availability of the Aqua interface and Apple made many changes to the UI based on customer feedback.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Mac OS X Public Beta expired and ceased to function in Spring 2001.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] On March 24, 2001, Apple released Mac OS X 10.0 (internally codenamed Cheetah).
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] The initial version was slow, incomplete, and had very few applications available at launch, mostly from independent developers.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] While many critics suggested that the operating system was not ready for mainstream adoption, they recognized the importance of its initial launch as a base on which to improve.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Simply releasing Mac OS X was received by the Macintosh community as a great accomplishment, for attempts to overhaul the Mac OS had been underway since 1996, and had been delayed by countless setbacks.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Later that year, on September 25, 2001, Mac OS X 10.1 (internally codenamed Puma) was released.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] It featured increased performance and provided missing features, such as DVD playback.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Apple released 10.1 as a free upgrade CD for 10.0 users, in addition to the $129 boxed version for people running Mac OS 9.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] It was discovered that the upgrade CDs were full install CDs that could be used with Mac OS 9 systems by removing a specific file; Apple later re-released the CDs in an actual stripped-down format that did not facilitate installation on such systems.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] On January 7, 2002, Apple announced that Mac OS X was to be the default operating system for all Macintosh products by the end of that month.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] On August 23, 2002, Apple followed up with Mac OS X 10.2 Jaguar, the first release to use its code name as part of the branding.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] It brought significant performance improvements, and an updated version of Aqua's visual design.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] The Happy Mac icon — which had appeared during the Mac OS startup sequence since the original Macintosh — was replaced with a gray Apple logo.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Mac OS X v10.3 Panther was released on October 24, 2003.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] It significantly improved performance and incorporated the most extensive update yet to the user interface.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Support for some early G3 computers such as "beige" Power Macs and "WallStreet" PowerBooks was discontinued.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Mac OS X 10.4 Tiger was released on April 29, 2005.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Apple stated that Tiger contained more than 200 new features.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] As with Panther, certain older machines were no longer supported; Tiger requires a Mac with 256 MB of RAM and a built-in FireWire port.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Among the new features, Tiger introduced Spotlight, Dashboard, Smart Folders, updated Mail program with Smart Mailboxes, QuickTime 7, Safari 2, Automator, VoiceOver, Core Image and Core Video.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] The initial release of the Apple TV used a modified version of Tiger with a different graphical interface and fewer applications and services.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] On January 10, 2006, Apple released the first Intel-based Macs along with the 10.4.4 update to Tiger.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] This operating system functioned identically on the PowerPC-based Macs and the new Intel-based machines, with the exception of the Intel release lacking support for the Classic environment.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Mac OS X 10.5 Leopard was released on October 26, 2007.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] It was called by Apple "the largest update of Mac OS X".
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Leopard supports both PowerPC- and Intel x86-based Macintosh computers; support for the G3 processor was dropped and the G4 processor required a minimum clock rate of 867 MHz, and at least 512 MB of RAM to be installed.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] The single DVD works for all supported Macs (including 64-bit machines).
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] New features include a new look, an updated Finder, Time Machine, Spaces, Boot Camp pre-installed, full support for 64-bit applications (including graphical applications), new features in Mail and iChat, and a number of new security features.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Leopard is an Open Brand UNIX 03 registered product on the Intel platform.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] It was also the first BSD-based OS to receive UNIX 03 certification.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Leopard dropped support for the Classic Environment and all Classic applications.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] It was the final version of Mac OS X to support the PowerPC architecture.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Mac OS X 10.6 Snow Leopard was released on August 28, 2009.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Rather than delivering big changes to the appearance and end user functionality like the previous releases of Mac OS X, Snow Leopard focused on "under the hood" changes, increasing the performance, efficiency, and stability of the operating system.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Snow Leopard only supported machines with Intel CPUs, required at least 1 GB of RAM, and dropped default support for applications built for the PowerPC architecture (Rosetta could be installed as an additional component to retain support for PowerPC-only applications).
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Snow Leopard also featured new 64-bit technology capable of supporting greater amounts of RAM, improved support for multi-core processors through Grand Central Dispatch, and advanced GPU performance with OpenCL.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] The 10.6.6 update also introduced support for the Mac App Store, Apple's digital distribution platform for macOS applications.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] OS X 10.7 Lion was released on July 20, 2011.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] It brought developments made in Apple's iOS, such as an easily navigable display of installed applications called Launchpad and a greater use of multi-touch gestures, to the Mac.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] This release removed Rosetta, making it incompatible with PowerPC applications.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Changes made to the GUI include auto-hiding scrollbars that only appear when they are used, and Mission Control which unifies Exposé, Spaces, Dashboard, and full-screen applications within a single interface.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Apple also made changes to applications: they resume in the same state as they were before they were closed, similar to iOS.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] OS X 10.8 Mountain Lion was released on July 25, 2012.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Following the release of Lion the previous year, it was the first of the annual rather than two-yearly updates to OS X (and later macOS), which also closely aligned with the annual iOS operating system updates.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] It incorporates some features seen in iOS 5, which include Game Center, support for iMessage in the new Messages messaging application, and Reminders as a to-do list app separate from iCal (which is renamed as Calendar, like the iOS app).
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] It also includes support for storing iWork documents in iCloud.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Notification Center, which makes its debut in Mountain Lion, is a desktop version similar to the one in iOS 5.0 and higher.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Application pop-ups are now concentrated on the corner of the screen, and the Center itself is pulled from the right side of the screen.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Mountain Lion also includes more Chinese features including support for Baidu as an option for Safari search engine, QQ, 163.com and 126.com services for Mail, Contacts and Calendar, Youku, Tudou and Sina Weibo are integrated into share sheets.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Starting with Mountain Lion, Apple software updates (including the OS) are distributed via the App Store.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] This updating mechanism replaced the Apple Software Update utility.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] OS X 10.9 Mavericks was released on October 22, 2013.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] It is a free upgrade to all users running Snow Leopard or later with a 64-bit Intel processor.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Its changes include the addition of the previously iOS-only Maps and iBooks applications, improvements to the Notification Center, enhancements to several applications, and many under-the-hood improvements.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] OS X 10.10 Yosemite was released on October 16, 2014.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] It features a redesigned user interface similar to that of iOS 7, intended to feature a more minimal, text-based 'flat' design, with use of translucency effects and intensely saturated colors.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Apple's showcase new feature in Yosemite is Handoff, which enables users with iPhones running iOS 8.1 or later to answer phone calls, receive and send SMS messages, and complete unfinished iPhone emails on their Mac.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] As of OS X 10.10.3, Photos replaced iPhoto and Aperture.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] OS X 10.11 El Capitan was released on September 30, 2015.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Similar to Mac OS X 10.6 Snow Leopard, Apple described this release as emphasizing "refinements to the Mac experience" and "improvements to system performance".
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Refinements include public transport built into the Maps application, GUI improvements to the Notes application, adopting San Francisco as the system font for clearer legibility, and the introduction of System Integrity Protection.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] The Metal API, first introduced in iOS 8, was also included in this operating system for "all Macs since 2012".
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] According to Apple, Metal accelerates system-level rendering by up to 50 percent, resulting in faster graphics performance for everyday apps.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Metal also delivers up to 10 times faster draw call performance for more fluid experience in games and pro apps.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] macOS 10.12 Sierra was released to the public on September 20, 2016.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] New features include the addition of Siri, optimized storage, and updates to Photos, Messages, and iTunes.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] macOS 10.13 High Sierra was released to the public on September 25, 2017.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Like OS X El Capitan and OS X Mountain Lion, High Sierra is a refinement-based update having very few new features visible to the user, including updates to Safari, Photos, and Mail, among other changes.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] The major change under the hood is the switch to the Apple File System, optimized for the solid-state storage used in most new Mac computers.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] macOS 10.14 Mojave was released on September 24, 2018.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] The update introduced a system-wide dark mode and several new apps lifted from iOS, such as Apple News.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] It was the first version to require a GPU that supports Metal.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Mojave also changed the system software update mechanism from the App Store (where it had been since OS X Mountain Lion) to a new panel in System Preferences.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] macOS 10.15 Catalina was released on October 7, 2019.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Updates included enhanced voice control, and bundled apps for music, video, and podcasts that together replace the functions of iTunes, and the ability to use an iPad as an external monitor.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Catalina officially dropped support for 32-bit applications.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] macOS Big Sur was announced during the WWDC keynote speech on June 22, 2020, and it was made available to the general public on November 12, 2020.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] This is the first time the major version number of the operating system has been incremented since the Mac OS X Public Beta in 2000.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] It brings Arm support, new icons, and aesthetic user interface changes to the system.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] macOS Ventura was announced during the WWDC keynote speech on June 6, 2022 and released on October 24, 2022.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] It came with the redesigned System Preferences (named System Settings) to a more iOS-like design, and the new Freeform, Weather and Clock apps that run natively on Mac.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Users can use an iPhone as a webcam for video conferencing with Continuity Camera.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Siri's appearance was changed to look more like the versions on iOS 14 and iPadOS 14.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Mail introduced schedule send and undo send for emails, and Message also got the ability to undo send and edit messages.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Stage Manager was introduced as a new way to organize all open windows in a desktop.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Maps gained the feature for multiple-stop routes, Metal 3 was added with support for spatial and temporal image upscaling, Lockdown Mode was added to reduce the risk of a cyberattack, and the ability to play ambient background sounds was added as an accessibility feature in System Settings.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] macOS Sonoma was announced during the WWDC keynote speech on June 5, 2023, and released on September 26, 2023. macOS Sonoma revamped widgets—they can now be placed anywhere on the desktop.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Game mode optimizes game performance by prioritizing gaming tasks and allocating more GPU and CPU capacity to the game, and by doing so is able to provide smoother frame rates for gameplay.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] The Spotlight Search bar and all app icons were made even more rounded, smoother animations were implemented for notifications and the lock screen, and new slow-motion screensavers of different locations worldwide were added.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] When logged in, they gradually slow down and become the desktop wallpaper.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] macOS Sequoia was announced during the WWDC keynote speech on June 10, 2024.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] macOS Tahoe was announced on June 9, 2025, during the WWDC 2025 keynote address.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] It is the first macOS version to feature the new Liquid Glass design introduced across Apple operating systems that year.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] It is also the first macOS to use Apple's new release number convention, which gives all of Apple's operating systems the same version number.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] macOS Golden Gate was announced at WWDC on June 8, 2026.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] It introduces visual intelligence, redesigns Siri, and brings Apple Intelligence features to apps such as Safari and Passwords.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Golden Gate also improves Liquid Glass on windows and sidebars, and allows users to adjust the system opacity.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Apple publishes Apple Platform Security documents to lay out the security protections built into macOS and Mac hardware.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] These prevent some vulnerabilities within macOS.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Only the latest major release of macOS (macOS Tahoe as of June 2026) receives patches for all known security vulnerabilities.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] The previous two releases receive some security updates, but not for all vulnerabilities known to Apple.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] macOS Ventura added support for Rapid Security Response (RSR) updates and Lockdown Mode.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Rapid Security Response updates may require a reboot, but take less than a minute to install.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] In an analysis, Hackintosh developer Mykola Grymalyuk noted that RSR updates can only fix userland vulnerabilities, and cannot patch the macOS kernel.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Lockdown Mode is an optional security feature designed to provide extreme protection for users who may be at risk of targeted cyberattacks, such as journalists, activists, and public figures.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] This mode significantly alters the functionality of the device to enhance security against sophisticated threats, particularly from spyware and state-sponsored attacks.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Apple says most people are never impacted by these attacks.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] In its earlier years, Mac OS X enjoyed a near-absence of the types of malware and spyware that have affected Microsoft Windows users. macOS has a smaller usage share compared to Windows.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Worms, as well as potential vulnerabilities, were noted in 2006, which led some industry analysts and anti-virus companies to issue warnings that Apple's Mac OS X is not immune to malware.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Increasing market share coincided with additional reports of a variety of attacks.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] In early 2011, Mac OS X experienced a large increase in malware attacks, and malware such as Mac Defender, MacProtector, and MacGuard was seen as an increasing problem for Mac users.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] At first, the malware installer required the user to enter the administrative password, but later versions installed without user input.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Initially, Apple support staff were instructed not to assist in the removal of the malware or admit the existence of the malware issue, but as the malware spread, a support document was issued.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Apple announced an OS X update to fix the problem.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] An estimated 100,000 users were affected.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] Apple releases security updates for macOS regularly, as well as signature files containing malware signatures for Xprotect, an anti-malware feature part of File Quarantine present since Mac OS X Snow Leopard.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] As of January 2023, macOS is the second-most widely used general-purpose desktop operating system used on the World Wide Web following Microsoft Windows, with a 15.33% usage share, according to statistics compiled by StatCounter.
[src:catalyst-mac/macos-p02] As a device company, Apple has mostly promoted macOS to sell Macs, with promotion of macOS updates focused on existing users, promotion at Apple Store and other retail partners, or through events for developers.
[src:catalyst-mac/swiftui] SwiftUI is declarative, contrasting with the imperative syntax used in other Apple development frameworks such as UIKit and AppKit.
[src:catalyst-mac/swiftui] SwiftUI allows for 2D drawing, animations, event handling, widgets, and data binding.
[src:catalyst-mac/swiftui] SwiftUI automatically synchronizes between UI views and data.
[src:catalyst-mac/swiftui] SwiftUI integrates with other Apple technologies, such as Xcode and Swift Playgrounds to provide for real-time previews during editing, alongside support for debugging and other development features.
[src:catalyst-mac/swiftui] SwiftUI allows for interoperability with UIKit and AppKit views via the `UIViewRepresentable` and `NSViewRepresentable` protocols respectively.
[src:catalyst-mac/swiftui] SwiftUI was announced at the company's Worldwide Developers Conference (WWDC) on June 3, 2019, and was added in iOS 13 and macOS Catalina.
[src:catalyst-mac/swiftui] During WWDC 2020 and the iOS 14 release cycle, Apple natively added support for maps with the `Map` view, with an interface based on Apple Maps via MapKit.
[src:catalyst-mac/swiftui] MapKit allows for map annotation and satellite imagery.
[src:catalyst-mac/swiftui] During WWDC 2021 and the iOS 15 release cycle, Apple added the `Canvas` element, adding support for Immediate mode drawing and performant 2D drawing.
[src:catalyst-mac/swiftui] During WWDC 2022 and the iOS 16 release cycle, Apple released Swift Charts, a framework for making customizable and accessible charts.
[src:catalyst-mac/swiftui] During WWDC 2023, Apple announced the Apple Vision Pro, and support for the device was added to SwiftUI, alongside new views for AR content such as `RealityView` and `ImmersiveSpace`.
[src:catalyst-mac/swiftui] The following is an example of a simple Hello World program.
[src:catalyst-mac/swiftui] The `@main` attribute defines the entry point into the app.
[src:catalyst-mac/swiftui] It is standard practice in SwiftUI to separate the application struct and views into different structs, according to the Model–View–ViewModel (MVVM) architectural pattern.
[src:catalyst-mac/uikit] UIKit provides an abstraction layer of iOS, the operating system for the iPhone, iPod Touch, and iPad.
[src:catalyst-mac/uikit] UIKit is similar to AppKit from the macOS Cocoa API toolset, and it too is primarily written in the Objective-C language.
[src:catalyst-mac/uikit] UIKit allows the use of hardware and features that are not found in macOS computers and are thus unique to the iOS range of devices.
[src:catalyst-mac/uikit] Like AppKit, UIKit follows a Model–View–Controller (MVC) software architecture.
[src:catalyst-mac/uikit] UIKit contains a different set of graphical control elements from AppKit.
[src:catalyst-mac/uikit] Tools for developing applications based on UIKit are included in the iOS SDK.
[src:catalyst-mac/uikit] iOS, watchOS, and tvOS technologies can be seen as a set of layers, with UIKit at the highest level and the core operating system / kernel at the bottom.
[src:catalyst-mac/uikit] UIKit provides the key frameworks for developing applications on devices running iOS, and is based atop Foundation Kit.
[src:catalyst-mac/uikit] Microsoft's WinObjC, the GNUstep-based iOS bridge for the Universal Windows Platform, contains working implementations of frameworks such as Foundation, UIKit, and MapKit released under the MIT License.
[src:catalyst-mac/uikit] One of the UIKit implementations is based on XAML.
